<Layout title="How to Handle a Low Offer on Your Brisbane Property | Daniel Gierach Property" description="Why low offers happen, how to counter-offer without burning the buyer relationship, what information to use in negotiations, and when walking away is the right call." draft={draft}>

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Should I counter-offer a low offer on my Brisbane property?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "In most cases, yes. A low offer is almost always worth countering unless it is so far below the market that engaging with it would signal weakness or set a damaging anchor for further negotiation. A counter-offer keeps the buyer in the conversation, gives them a clear signal about where the price needs to be, and moves the negotiation forward. Declining to engage entirely is usually only the right call when a buyer has made a calculated lowball in a slow market and you have other genuine interest to work with instead."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What counts as a low offer in Brisbane real estate?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A low offer is one that is materially below what comparable sales data and current market conditions support for your property. In Brisbane's inner east, an offer that is 5% below a well-founded asking price is a normal starting point for negotiation. An offer that is 10% or more below what comparable evidence supports is more accurately described as a low offer. Context matters too: in a strong seller's market with multiple interested buyers, an offer 8% below asking is low. In a slower market with few competing buyers, the same offer might be a reasonable opening."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "When should I reject a low offer outright rather than countering?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Rejecting a low offer without countering is worth considering when you have other genuine interest from buyers who are closer to your price expectations, when the offer is so far below market value that engaging would harm your negotiating position with other buyers, or when the buyer has demonstrated through their behaviour that they are not serious. In most other circumstances, a polite counter-offer is a more effective response than a flat rejection, because it preserves the relationship and gives the buyer a clear indication of where the sale is likely to transact."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

  <!-- Hero -->
  <div style="background:#0a0806;padding:8rem 0 3rem;">
