      <a href="/insights" style="display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:0.5rem;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.35);text-decoration:none;margin-bottom:2rem;transition:color 0.2s;"
        onmouseover="this.style.color='#f5d07a'" onmouseout="this.style.color='rgba(240,236,228,0.35)'">
        &larr; All Articles
      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers &middot; 5 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        How to Handle a Low Offer on Your Brisbane Property
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        A low offer is rarely the end of a negotiation. How you respond in the next 24 hours determines whether that buyer becomes your purchaser or disappears.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Receiving a low offer on a property you have prepared carefully and priced honestly is frustrating. The instinct is often to decline it or to respond in a way that signals just how far off the mark it is. Both of those instincts, if acted on without thought, can cost you money. How you handle a low offer is a skill, and the agents who consistently achieve strong sale prices for their vendors have usually mastered the response to a low offer as much as any other part of the selling process.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why low offers happen</h2>
      <p>Low offers arrive for a range of reasons, and understanding the reason behind a specific offer is useful information for deciding how to respond. Some buyers test the market as a matter of habit: they make low offers on every property they consider and adjust based on the response. They are not necessarily disrespectful or unserious; it is simply their default strategy. These buyers often have a genuine ceiling that is closer to the market than their opening offer suggests.</p>

      <p>Some buyers have been outbid or disappointed elsewhere and are anchoring to a lower price as an emotional response to a recent loss. They need to be brought along gently, with clear comparable sales information, rather than rejected sharply. Others have a different view of the property's value, either because they have done their own research and genuinely believe the market evidence supports a lower price, or because they are planning to use the property in a way (knockdown, significant renovation, investment) that produces different economics from an owner-occupier's assessment.</p>

      <p>And some buyers are simply not the right buyers for your property. They are not in a position to transact at a price that reflects what the property is worth, and no amount of negotiation will bridge the gap. Knowing which type of buyer you are dealing with is the first task after receiving a low offer, and your agent should be gathering that information before you decide on a response.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The emotional response versus the strategic response</h2>
      <p>The emotional response to a low offer is to decline it immediately, often with language that communicates the vendor's displeasure. This feels satisfying and it protects the vendor's sense of the property's worth. It is also almost always the wrong response. Declining a low offer abruptly closes the door on a buyer who might have been negotiable, sends a signal to the market that the vendor is emotional or inflexible, and occasionally leaves money on the table when that buyer walks away and never returns.</p>

      <p>The strategic response is to treat a low offer as the opening of a conversation rather than an insult. That means acknowledging the offer, giving the buyer a clear indication through a counter-offer that their number is not close to where the sale will transact, and using that counter to set a more realistic anchor for the next round of negotiation. The counter should be direct, not hedged. A counter-offer that is close to your asking price communicates that you are not prepared to discount significantly. A counter-offer that lands somewhere in the middle of the gap between their offer and your asking price invites further negotiation that may not be in your interest.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What information justifies your counter</h2>
      <p>A counter-offer is more effective when it is accompanied by evidence rather than assertion. The three most powerful pieces of information your agent can bring to a negotiation conversation with a low buyer are: recent comparable sales in the same suburb and price bracket that demonstrate what equivalent properties have achieved, a clear articulation of the competing interest in the property (if other buyers are close to or at your asking price, the low buyer needs to know they are in competition), and an honest summary of what the campaign has demonstrated about buyer demand so far.</p>

      <p>Comparable sales data addresses the most common reason buyers give for low offers: "We don't think it's worth that much." If the recent sales evidence clearly supports your price, presenting it firmly removes the theoretical basis for the low offer. A buyer who has convinced themselves a property is worth less than the market says it is will often adjust their position when presented with clear evidence, particularly if they have genuine interest in the property and do not want to lose it.</p>

      <p>Competing interest is the most powerful tool in a negotiation, but it must be used honestly. If you have three other buyers at or near your asking price, your agent can and should convey that to the low buyer. If you have no other active buyers, fabricating interest to pressure a low buyer is both unethical and likely to backfire when the buyer tests whether the competition is real.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When to walk away from a low offer</h2>
      <p>There are circumstances where the right response to a low offer is not to engage further. If the buyer is more than 15% to 20% below what comparable sales clearly support and your campaign has been running for less than two to three weeks, you almost certainly have more buyers to come. Spending your negotiating energy on a buyer who is nowhere near the market reduces your focus on the buyers who are genuinely close to your price expectations. Your agent's judgement about which buyers to prioritise during a campaign is part of what you are paying for.</p>

      <p>In a slower market, with limited competing interest and a campaign that has been running for several weeks without offers at your asking price, the calculus is different. A buyer who is 10% below your price in a soft market with no other offers in sight deserves more negotiating attention than the same buyer in a strong market with three others behind them. The right response depends heavily on where you are in the campaign and what your agent is observing about buyer activity and sentiment.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How your agent manages the negotiation conversation</h2>
      <p>One of the least visible but most valuable things a good agent does is manage the negotiation conversation so that the vendor does not have to be directly involved in it. When you are negotiating directly with a buyer, the emotional stakes are higher, the risk of saying something that weakens your position is greater, and the buyer can read your reaction in real time. When your agent is carrying the conversation, there is a professional buffer that allows information to be communicated deliberately and without the emotional charge that direct vendor-buyer negotiation often carries.</p>

      <p>Your agent should be reporting back to you on the substance of the conversation, the buyer's motivations and situation, and their recommendation on how to respond at each step. The decision on how to proceed is yours. The execution of the negotiation conversation, including when to push and when to pause, is your agent's role. This is the version of the process that consistently produces the best outcomes for vendors, and it is one of the reasons that experienced seller's agents justify their commission in strong market conditions.</p>

      <div style="padding:1.5rem;background:rgba(245,208,122,0.06);border-left:3px solid #f5d07a;">
        <p style="font-size:0.88rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.8;"><strong style="color:#f5d07a;">Received a low offer and not sure how to respond?</strong> Daniel can give you a clear read on whether the offer is negotiable, what the comparable evidence says, and how to approach the next step without leaving money on the table. <a href="/contact" style="color:#f5d07a;font-weight:600;">Get in touch.</a></p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</article>
